               <interp inst="t18791020-987" type="date" value="18791020"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18791020-987-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-987-18791020 t18791020-987-offence-1 t18791020-987-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>987. <persName id="def1-987-18791020" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-987-18791020" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-987-18791020" type="age" value="28"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-987-18791020" type="surname" value="BATEMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-987-18791020" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE BATEMAN</hi> (28)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18791020-987-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18791020-987-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18791020-987-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>, Stealing 9lb. of white lead and 1 pint of turpentine, the goods of <persName id="t18791020-name-642" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-642" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-642" type="surname" value="DURRANT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-642" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18791020-987-offence-1 t18791020-name-642"></join>Thomas Durrant</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PURCELL</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Prosecuted; and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BLACKWELL</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Defended.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18791020-name-643" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-643" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-643" type="surname" value="DIX"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-643" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY DIX</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a painter at 19, St. Mary's Place, Rotherhithe, and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187910200181"></xptr>
               <p>work for Mr. Thomas Durrant, of Trinity Street—the prisoner came and spoke to me while I was working on the 2nd inst., and alter he left I missed 9 1/2 lb. of white lead and a pint of turpentine—I gave information to a constable and went the same afternoon to the prisoner's house in Windmill Lane, and found some of the white lead there in a tin belonging to me—I was afterwards shown some turpentine in this bottle (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) which I identitied as my master's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> The job was at some houses belonging to the Surrey Canal Company, and it was not an open place—there is a constable's lodge—the house is being done up for the deputy superintendent—we have to go through a gate—a number of persons were passing in and out—there would be no special watch kept, but there is a man there all day to see what goes in and out—it might have been seen and taken no notice of—only myself and son were working on the job, but he was not down there—the carpenters left their tools on the floors at night, and we always found them in the morning as we had left them—it was 3 p.m. when the prisoner came to me and asked where my son was, and I said upstairs; I thought he was going up to speak to him and did not notice him as I was at my work—when I missed the lead I went to my son and asked if the prisoner had been to speak to him, and he said, "No."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18791020-name-644" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-644" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-644" type="surname" value="NOLAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-644" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN NOLAN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman R</hi> 13). On 2nd September, about 4 p.m., 1 stopped the prisoner—I found in his breast pocket this bottle of turpentine—I said, "How did you come by that?"—he said, "It belongs to me," and then Dix came up, and in consequence of what he said we went to the prisoner's house and found the white lead in his room—his house was about half a mile or more from where Dix was working, and about 200 yards from where I stopped him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18791020-name-645" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-645" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-645" type="surname" value="TOLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-645" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES TOLEY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman R</hi>). I went with the last witness to the prisoner's house, 10, Windmill Lane, on the 2nd, about 6 p.m.—we found in his bedroom this tin bath (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) under the bed, and four chairs (<hi rend="italic">one produced</hi>) in the front room—the prisoner and his wife occupied two rooms—I saw a carpet there, but a man named Lott was there, and from what he said I did not take it, but in consequence of what I heard I went back and it was gone—I afterwards found it at 8, Southwark Park Road, Bermondsey, rolled up as produced—Lott was in the room with it—I then went to the prisoner and he was further charged with having the bath and chairs in his possession, knowing them to have been stolen—he said, "I bought the bath of a man. I don't know him. I bought the chairs of a man named Lott."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> They had only occupied the room in Windmill Street one night—the prisoner was in custody when the carpet was found—I did not see it while he was there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> He was in custody at the station when I went to his house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18791020-name-646" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-646" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-646" type="surname" value="SKULL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-646" type="given" value="EDWIN GEORGE"></interp>EDWIN GEORGE SKULL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an oil and colourman at 229, Lower Road, Rotherhithe—this bath is mine—I last saw it on 29th August about 10 p.m, outside my door—my man was just shuttiug up—I went in to speak to him and when I came out the bath was gone.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18791020-name-647" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-647" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-647" type="surname" value="AN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-647" type="given" value="EMMA NE"></interp>EMMA NE AN</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 11, Cornberry Road, Deptford—on 29th August, about 11 o'clock, I sent my little girl on an errand, and she left the door ajar—I and my husband were in the kitchen—she came back and</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187910200182"></xptr>
               <p>from what she said I went to the front room and found the window wide open and four chairs gone—I have seen and identified the chairs—the window was fastened before my little girl went out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18791020-name-648" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-648" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-648" type="surname" value="BENNETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18791020-name-648" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BENNETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a furniture dealer at 185, High Street, Deptford—on Saturday, 30th August, a Brussels carpet was put outside my shop for sale and I saw it safe about 7 p.m., and about 9.4 it was gone—I told the police, and on 2nd September I identified the carpet at Rotherhithe Police-station—I value it at 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> There were three of us in the shop, but we were busy—there were thousands of people passing.</p>
               <p>
